# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: os-book
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:os-book/initialization] When a computer is first started, it is in an unknown state.
[src:os-book/initialization] Static electricity and remnants of previous states can lead to values that are not valid states for the machine.
[src:os-book/initialization] In defense, computer programmers have learned to initialize all variables before using them.
[src:os-book/initialization] For large mainframe computers, the Initial Program Load, or IPL, is used to load a bootstrap program, typically very tiny, whose purpose is to load the actual boot loader from disk, tape or other media.
[src:os-book/initialization] For typical desktop, server, or rack-mounted blade computers, the power-on-self-test or POST initializes the computer, which then passes execution over to the ROM, where the BIOS system initializes the bottom page or so of RAM, then passes execution to the boot process.
[src:os-book/initialization] One of the first things that the boot process does is load the boot loader, which then loads the operating system.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] The kernel is the core of an operating system.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] It is the software responsible for running programs and providing secure access to the machine's hardware.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] Since there are many programs, and resources are limited, the kernel also decides when and how long a program should run.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] Accessing the hardware directly can be very complex, since there are many different hardware designs for the same type of component.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] Kernels usually implement some level of hardware abstraction (a set of instructions universal to all devices of a certain type) to hide the underlying complexity from applications and provide a clean and uniform interface.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] This helps application programmers to develop programs without having to know how to program for specific devices.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] The kernel relies upon software drivers that translate the generic command into instructions specific to that device.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] An operating system kernel is not strictly needed to run a computer.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] Programs can be directly loaded and executed on the "bare metal" machine, provided that the authors of those programs are willing to do without any hardware abstraction or operating system support.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] This was the normal operating method of many early computers, which were reset and reloaded between the running of different programs.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] Eventually, small ancillary programs such as program loaders and debuggers were typically left in-core between runs, or loaded from read-only memory.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] As these were developed, they formed the basis of what became early operating system kernels.
[src:os-book/kernel-architecture] The "bare metal" approach is still used today on many video game consoles and embedded systems, but in general, newer systems use kernels and operating systems.
[src:os-book/memory-management] Memory Management is a term used to describe how the operating system handles the available RAM.
[src:os-book/memory-management] At the most basic level, there is the physical memory.
[src:os-book/memory-management] The physical memory's size is the sum of the capacities of all RAM-modules (such as DDR SDRAM) installed in the system.
[src:os-book/memory-management] For example, when you have two 512 MiB DDR SDRAM modules installed in your system, the OS will have 1 GiB of physical memory at its disposal.
[src:os-book/memory-management] On top of the physical memory is the segmented memory.
[src:os-book/memory-management] It uses the Memory Management Unit (MMU) to translate a logical address (specifying a segment and an offset) into a physical address (or linear address).
[src:os-book/memory-management] This allowed early computers to address more than 64 KiB of memory.
[src:os-book/memory-management] Most operating systems today don't use a segmented memory model, preferring to use paging.
[src:os-book/memory-management] A paged memory model uses the MMU to translate virtual addresses to physical addresses.
[src:os-book/memory-management] With paging, one can map multiple 4 KiB-sized chunks (called pages) to any virtual address.
[src:os-book/memory-management] For example, data at offset 0x1000 in physical memory might be mapped to address 0xC0000000 (at offset 3 GiB) in virtual memory, even though the system may have only 32 MiB of physical RAM available.
[src:os-book/memory-management] Accessing the data at address 0xC0000000 internally accesses the data at physical address 0x1000.
[src:os-book/memory-management] This provides processes with their own virtual address space which contains only the code and data required by that single process, and everything else is hidden.
[src:os-book/memory-management] This way, a process can't corrupt another process' code or data, improving security and reliability.
[src:os-book/memory-management] With paging, memory is managed in 4 KiB-sized chunks.
[src:os-book/memory-management] Most applications require the ability to be able to get only a fraction of that size, to store data.
[src:os-book/memory-management] The memory allocator gets a big chunk of memory (say, 4 pages, or 4 * 4 KiB) and divides this into much smaller chunks (e.g. a chunk of 16 bytes and another chunk of 6 bytes.) which it gives to the applications when requested.
[src:os-book/memory-management] Many Languages and some operating systems use a form of allocated memory called a HEAP, essentially one large space where memory can be used and re-used.
[src:os-book/memory-management] The fragmentation effect results in lots of small unusable spaces spread throughout the heap.
[src:os-book/memory-management] Garbage collection may for instance involve the movement of an allocated memory from one location to another in order to free up more space.
[src:os-book/memory-management] To achieve this transparently to the memory, the allocation unit address must not be the same as the public address, but the public address must be a reference to a look-up table that contains the allocation unit address.
[src:os-book/memory-management] The garbage collector can then write a copy of the data to a new address, and then change the look-up table address before removing the original data and allowing the consolidation process to recover the space.
[src:os-book/memory-management] Another technique is to reference the start and end point of each allocated memory unit, and when a memory unit is released, test to see if the unit before and after it are either free, and if so reallocate a larger block that contains all the free sections that are contiguous.
[src:os-book/memory-management] During allocation the allocation utility will start at the top of the list of free sections and look to see if any are exactly the size requested, if so, the first that fits will be selected, then the next largest one if none are found the exact size.
[src:os-book/memory-management] Garbage collection can be done continuously or at low use times, with the eventual caveat that if no low use times are found, the garbage collection will cause the whole computer to slow down temporarily when fragmentation becomes unwieldy.
[src:os-book/microprocessor-design] This book serves as an introduction to the field of microprocessor design and implementation.
[src:os-book/microprocessor-design] It is intended for students in computer science or computer or electrical engineering who are in the third or fourth years of an undergraduate degree.
[src:os-book/microprocessor-design] While the focus of this book will be on microprocessors, many of the concepts will apply to other ASIC design tasks as well.
[src:os-book/microprocessor-design] The reader should have prior knowledge in digital circuits and possibly some background in semiconductors although it isn't strictly necessary.
[src:os-book/microprocessor-design] The reader also should know at least one assembly language.
[src:os-book/microprocessor-design] Knowledge of higher-level languages such as C or C++ may be useful as well, but are not required.
[src:os-book/microprocessor-design] Sections about soft-core design will require prior knowledge of programmable logic, and a prior knowledge of at least one HDL (hardware description language).
